r {\\n\\n    @Override\\n    protected Configuration createConfiguration(RoundEnvironment roundEnv) {\\n        try {\\n            Class<? extends Annotation> entity = Entity.class;\\n            Class<? extends Annotation> superType = MappedSuperclass.class;\\n            Class<? extends Annotation> embeddable = Embeddable.class;\\n            Class<? extends Annotation> embedded = Embedded.class;\\n            Class<? extends Annotation> skip = Transient.class;\\n            return new HibernateConfiguration(roundEnv, processingEnv, entity, superType,\\n                    embeddable, embedded, skip);\\n        } catch (ClassNotFoundException e) {\\n            throw new RuntimeException(e);\\n        }\\n    }\\n\\n}\\n\"}], \"isError\": false, \"timestamp\": 1778571101372}]}\nhuman-intervention-logs/com.querydsl:querydsl-apt:5.0.0/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-12T07-33-31-742554Z.log:1653:[thinking] I'm reflecting on compiling the source with HibernateAnnotationProcessor and asserting the generated Q class. Dynamic access looks good in the processor configuration, and it seems like there's no need for a stub here, which feels idiomatic. I wonder if there could be potential issues with JavaCompiler in a native image, particularly regarding source generation, given that the existing test did that. I want to ensure that everything runs under 60 seconds. Querydsl processor might handle scanning and generating, so that seems alright.\nhuman-intervention-logs/com.querydsl:querydsl-apt:5.0.0/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-12T07-33-31-742554Z.log:1667:[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Considering Hibernate and Querydsl**\\n\\nI'm reflecting on compiling the source with HibernateAnnotationProcessor and asserting the generated Q class. Dynamic access looks good in the processor configuration, and it seems like there's no need for a stub here, which feels idiomatic. I wonder if there could be potential issues with JavaCompiler in a native image, particularly regarding source generation, given that the existing test did that. I want to ensure that everything runs under 60 seconds. Querydsl processor might handle scanning and generating, so that seems alright.\\n\\n**Clarifying native image classpath**\\n\\nI'm considering the problem of native images not having a JAR file classpath. In a native-image test, it seems that dependencies rely on the image heap/classes rather than the filesystem's classpath. So if the JavaCompiler is compiling code that imports these dependencies into a native executable, it could fail to locate them because there are no classpath entries available. This definitely requires careful handling of dependencies when working with native images!\\n\\n**Evaluating Hibernate Dependencies**\\n\\nI need to ensure that Class.forName has access to the necessary Hibernate classes during test runtime. To do this, I’ll add the hibernate-core dependency. It looks like the JPAConfiguration class will need JPA, likely through hibernate-core. Although Hibernate 5.6 relies on javax.persistence-api 2.2, the test source might not be importing JPA. We may also need to define annotation arguments and load javax.persistence classes through hibernate-core, possibly with an explicit inclusion of jakarta.persistence-api. That seems wise.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_02e09efad86dd3ce016a02d769e6b081a3bee79cd5527c6bc4\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABqAteJcm1SnJBAVs8CfK85ZZ4kSyel6DY2pC9KizibJlRttvQM1z6ffAMJLomlM5DPjtElHTcYDhb-xRf-mN_5SHp6qmHVUjrCoYGdXcYB7atTWN9l5YYOcfmAGe1QwxbB15UV_kn6ixttugSyScnEq1VKUQHqWA9i0ikIIVA7VYcfadxmax6t4a-Tz8qvcCmw0pOeOlrgzS0stxkj9mz3uqWxOK6V1a4azz05kjT-9mdBv7zVUh9qfjwd1qpeNfsilJKMM9Lw1u2DlvnNPkhV-kYkYSwwQAK9yjz7mSmdBBQSs-jgNWXMDnoMH9H8h4IW-UYHPSv85T18q4NM1osvaSFo8zE9KvM2KT3qlHKeYyWDBvYN0CAIc2agqJgdFFFcL6qaeU6HjIacrB3gKT3EQMy7ez4