Hibernate classes during test runtime. To do this, I’ll add the hibernate-core dependency. It looks like the JPAConfiguration class will need JPA, likely through hibernate-core. Although Hibernate 5.6 relies on javax.persistence-api 2.2, the test source might not be importing JPA. We may also need to define annotation arguments and load javax.persistence classes through hibernate-core, possibly with an explicit inclusion of jakarta.persistence-api. That seems wise.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_zxIh44WCHPmYyWpWxrDlOYAf|fc_02e09efad86dd3ce016a02d789643c81a3a5498533d79d1746\", \"name\": \"read\", \"arguments\": {\"path\": \"tests/src/com.querydsl/querydsl-apt/5.0.0/build/reports/dynamic-access/dynamic-access-coverage.json\", \"limit\": 100}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 813, \"output\": 2114, \"cacheRead\": 19968, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 22895, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1778571112572, \"responseId\": \"resp_02e09efad86dd3ce016a02d7693a5481a3b0f8d6a3712e3a43\"}}\nhuman-intervention-logs/com.querydsl:querydsl-apt:5.0.0/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-12T07-33-31-742554Z.log:1723:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Considering Hibernate and Querydsl**\\n\\nI'm reflecting on compiling the source with HibernateAnnotationProcessor and asserting the generated Q class. Dynamic access looks good in the processor configuration, and it seems like there's no need for a stub here, which feels idiomatic. I wonder if there could be potential issues with JavaCompiler in a native image, particularly regarding source generation, given that the existing test did that. I want to ensure that everything runs under 60 seconds. Querydsl processor might handle scanning and generating, so that seems alright.\\n\\n**Clarifying native image classpath**\\n\\nI'm considering the problem of native images not having a JAR file classpath. In a native-image test, it seems that dependencies rely on the image heap/classes rather than the filesystem's classpath. So if the JavaCompiler is compiling code that imports these dependencies into a native executable, it could fail to locate them because there are no classpath entries available. This definitely requires careful handling of dependencies when working with native images!\\n\\n**Evaluating Hibernate Dependencies**\\n\\nI need to ensure that Class.forName has access to the necessary Hibernate classes during test runtime. To do this, I’ll add the hibernate-core dependency. It looks like the JPAConfiguration class will need JPA, likely through hibernate-core. Although Hibernate 5.6 relies on javax.persistence-api 2.2, the test source might not be importing JPA. We may also need to define annotation arguments and load javax.persistence classes through hibernate-core, possibly with an explicit inclusion of jakarta.persistence-api. That seems wise.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_02e09efad86dd3ce016a02d769e6b081a3bee79cd5527c6bc4\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABqAteJcm1SnJBAVs8CfK85ZZ4kSyel6DY2pC9KizibJlRttvQM1z6ffAMJLomlM5DPjtElHTcYDhb-xRf-mN_5SHp6qmHVUjrCoYGdXcYB7atTWN9l5YYOcfmAGe1QwxbB15UV_kn6ixttugSyScnEq1VKUQHqWA9i0ikIIVA7VYcfadxmax6t4a-Tz8qvcCmw0pOeOlrgzS0stxkj9mz3uqWxOK6V1a4azz05kjT-9mdBv7zVUh9qfjwd1qpeNfsilJKMM9Lw1u2DlvnNPkhV-kYkYSwwQAK9yjz7mSmdBBQSs-jgNWXMDnoMH9H8h4IW-UYHPSv85T18q4NM1osvaSFo8zE9KvM2KT3qlHKeYyWDBvYN0CAIc2agqJgdFFFcL6qaeU6HjIacrB3gKT3EQMy7ez4prhA5BaPMYkjNlHsxrk3MSTjkQLhdDLZpbPZbeayIuiV3d3j1eyENoNSNEJw53RFLgt_EnTmv107g7J2JkY95jm6oZGhV50TdZgvqa_lGFhsTe1oBpeV5YflHwG9WgSlRIpZdG_qicYhiu2KSxoRaNSfMZxLZx9FNtCkBZmf9IZc0-d1d9cWTmXfQQ-VG9en5LgjIcNTFuekggUY35DggabTUd8YYqWuxbOlR5W2-g4stQTKobgsUa3yaMcD81s0V91NkIix_hHajg7EkWnOaC06ktZfC